  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "In the 1880s Reason Cowart founded a sawmill and country store at what became Cowart's Corner, sparking Ona's early growth.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12,
        20,
        21
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/ona-florida-ghost-town/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "By 1911 the railroad turned Ona into a bustling hub, linking western and central Florida through vital shipping routes.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2,
        5,
        26
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/ona-florida-ghost-town/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Solomon's Castle, built from discarded aluminum plates and found objects, now stands as Ona's eccentric three‑story artistic landmark.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        30,
        13,
        19
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/ona-florida-ghost-town/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "More than 300 whimsical artworks made from reclaimed materials adorn Solomon's Castle, and the castle’s tour script still uses the original puns written by Howard Solomon.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3,
        7
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.sarasotamagazine.com/travel-and-outdoors/2023/12/solomons-castle-ona-florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "After the local forest resources were depleted, the sawmill, store, and post office closed, leaving Ona a quiet rural community of fewer than 600 residents.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18,
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
